Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Remove the steaks from your
fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Pour enough oil into a
#baking tray{} to cover the bottom and pop into the oven. Bring a large
#saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Add the
potatoes to the boiling water and cook, ~{5-6%mins} or until the edges are
soft.

Meanwhile, trim and halve the @Chantenay carrots{150%g} lengthways. Pop onto
another baking tray. Drizzle with oil, season with salt and pepper then toss
to coat. Spread out in a single layer, then set aside.

Pick the @rosemary{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the
stalks). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Peel and
grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Crush the
@black peppercorns{1%tsp} with a #rolling pin{}.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, then pop back into the pan.
Sprinkle on the @garlic salt{1%tsp}, @plain flour{2%tbsp} and three quarters of
the rosemary. Shake to fluff up the potatoes, then carefully add them to the
hot baking tray, turning in the oil. Season with salt, then roast on the top
shelf until golden, ~{30-40%mins}.

After ~{10-15%mins}, add the carrots to the middle shelf of the oven to roast
until tender, ~{20-25%mins}. Turn the wedges and carrots halfway through.

Clean the potato pan and pop back on medium heat with a drizzle of oil. Once
hot, add the shallot and fry until soft, ~{4-5%mins}. Add the
@baby spinach{100%g} and garlic, then season with salt and pepper. Stir
together and cook until wilted, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir through half the @creme fraiche{150%g} and cook until piping hot,
~{1-2%mins}. Taste and season if needed, then remove from the heat. Cover
with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season the
@venison leg steaks{2} with salt, pepper and the remaining rosemary.

When hot, lay the venison into the pan and brown the meat for ~{1%minute} on
both sides. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1%minute} on each
side.

> Venison is best served rare but if you like it more well done, cook for another
> 2 mins on each side.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The venison
> is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once ready, transfer the steaks to a #board{} and allow to rest, loosely
covered with #foil{}.

Pop your (now empty) frying pan back on medium heat. Add the
@water{100%ml} for the sauce, @chicken stock paste{10%g} and crushed
peppercorns to the pan. Stir together, then allow to reduce until thickened,
~{2-3%mins}.

Stir in the remaining creme fraiche, then remove from the heat.

Thinly slice the venison widthways and serve with the rosemary wedges, carrots
and creamed spinach alongside. Spoon over the peppercorn sauce to finish.
Enjoy!